      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i need some help with some numbers. we're seeing a big spike in shrinkage at our warehouse lately and i need to figure out how this is actually affecting our inventory turnover ratio. can u show me how to calculate the adjusted ratio with the lost stock included?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To calculate the adjusted inventory turnover ratio, you'll need to modify your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) to account for the lost stock from shrinkage. The formula is typically: $\\text{Adjusted Turnover} = \\text{Adjusted COGS} / \\text{Average Inventory}$.\n\nFirst, you must calculate the Adjusted COGS by adding the value of the lost stock (shrinkage) to your standard COGS. Then, divide this new, higher figure by your average inventory value to see the true impact of the lost inventory. This adjusted ratio will give you a more accurate picture of how quickly you are actually selling through your goods.",
